did.abstract: Edward Ingraham was born in Bristol, Connecticut. He was the great-grandson of Elias Ingraham. Mr. Ingraham was the president of the E. Ingraham Company from 1927- 1954. He died in 1972 at the age of 85.

accessrestrict.head: Access
accessrestrict.p: The collection is open and available for research.

acqinfo.head: Acquisition Information
acqinfo.p: In January 1980 these papers were donated by Yale University Library to the University of Connecticut Libraries, and placed in Historical Manuscripts and Archives (now Archives & Special Collections), located in the Dodd Research Center.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Series I: Correspondence (undated, 1931-1959) contains a variety of materials, including correspondence, minutes of meetings' memoranda, and other types of papers. This series constitutes the core collection of Edward Ingraham Papers, initially donated to Yale University and arranged chronologically. Most of these papers relate to his 27-year career as president of E. Ingraham Company. In addition to official papers, the collection includes correspondence relating to his service as president of the Clock Manufacturers Association of America, the Manufacturers Association of Connecticut, the American Clock and Watch Museum in Bristol, as well as the Bristol Boys Association, also as director of the International Silver Company, the Bristol Brass Corporation, Associated Spring Cooperation of Bristol, and the Bristol Bank and Trust Company; and as chairman for Connecticut of the Wooden Crusade for the restoration of war-stricken churches in Germany and as well as an active committee member for the Connecticut Junior Republic, the Bristol Library, and the Yale University Class of 1910.

The papers are of historical, economic and social interest in their documentation of the development of the American clock and watch industry, the establishment of the American Clock and Watch museum, the effect of the Swiss Tariff issue on the American clock industry and on U.S. governmental and economic policies. Included are records dealing with various War Board Committees established by the federal government to formulate industrial policies for the course of the national defense. Labor History is documented in records of union company arbitration decisions, legal evaluations of their relevance to similar labor- management situations at the E. Ingraham Company, and extensive minutes of union-company meetings. The minutes, recorded by company lawyers, contain accounts of union management disputes, detailed reports of plant operations both technical and social, job descriptions, and memoranda on the attitudes and reactions of employee toward union and management. Special topics in business history include problems of the clock industry in the time of war, the role of the clock business in defense, technological and social problems of reconversion from war to peacetime production, and geographical can managerial problems of plant expansion. The role and responsibilities of the business administrator in civic and state affairs is documented by correspondence concerned with Mr. Ingraham's professional and social relationships with man of the clock and other vital industries.

In the area of Connecticut State and local history, the papers describe the E. Ingraham Company as a family business of essential importance to the people of Bristol, for whom the company was a major source of employment. The family dedication to the company is clearly seen in the professional relationship of Dudley and Edward Ingraham. The series also includes correspondence of special not between Mr. Ingraham and John Joseph Murphy, a graduate student of economics at Yale. Mr. Murphy used the E. Ingraham Company papers as the basis of a doctoral dissertation completed in 1961. His dissertation is entitled, The Establishment of the American Clock- Making Industry.

Series II: Select Correspondence (undated, 1841-1971) contains correspondence donated to Yale at a later date, which was arranged separately by name of correspondent. These individuals include family members, relatives, close friends, and others.

Series III: Personal Correspondence (undated, 1883-1964) also contains correspondence not included in the original collection of Edward Ingraham Papers. Most of the items in this series pre-date Series I. They include family letters, postcards from extensive travels by relatives and friends, and related materials, arranged chronologically.

Series IV: Writings (undated, 1940-1963) consists of Edward Ingraham's unpublished articles, speeches, reminiscences, research notes, and other writings. Major topics include the history of theE. Ingraham Company, clock-making, the impact of WWII on business, Ingraham family genealogy, personal reminiscences and autobiography, and related concerns.
Series V: Subject Files (undated, 1787-1969) contains a variety of materials relating to E. Ingraham activities and Edward Ingraham's personal interests. Files are arranged alphabetically by topic.

bioghist.head: Biography
bioghist.p: Edward Ingraham was born 20 December 1887, and raised in Bristol, CT. He was the great-grandson of Elias Ingraham, an entrepreneur in early American clock- making and the founder of the E. Ingraham Company, a manufacturer of clocks and non-jeweled watches. After graduating from Yale in 1910, he began his long association with the E. Ingraham Company. From 1927 - 1954, he served as president of the company.

In 1918, Mr. Ingraham married Alice Patti Pease, a French teacher in the Bristol High School. They had five children, four daughters (Alice, Grace, Ellen, and Faith), and a son, William Shurtleff Ingraham. After Mrs. Ingraham's death, Mr. Ingraham married Ethel Leishman Beach, a trust officer at the Bristol Bank and Trust Company on January 16, 1952. Ethel Ingraham was born 3 January 1895 in Bristol, the daughter of John and Agnes Turnbull Leishman.

Edward Ingraham possessed a deep concern for the tradition and craft of clock-making, evidenced by his active support for the establishment of a clock and watch museum, and his great sense of personal pride in the role of the Ingraham family in the industry's historical and technical history. He viewed the manufacture of time mechanisms as an activity vital to the security of the American people, especially in periods of national emergency.
Edward Ingraham died in 1972 at the age of 85. Ethel L. Ingraham died in 1980.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: The Edward Ingraham Papers (1787 - 1971, bulk 1931-1959) comprise the personal and business papers of Edward Ingraham (1887- 1972), president of E. Ingraham Company, a Bristol, Connecticut, manufacturer of clocks and watches. The papers include personal and business correspondence, a small quantity of E. Ingraham Company records, materials concerning the National Association of Clock and Watch Manufacturers, his writings about Connecticut clock- making, Ingraham family genealogy, personal reminiscences, and other topics.
